values:
The year ahead will bring me a changed way of life,&nbsp; 
and I am in the process of massively downsizing&nbsp;
and parting with much-loved possessions&nbsp; 
(especially my books!) 

&nbsp;But not all decisions have to be made immediately.&nbsp;&nbsp;
Stuart will only be with me at weekends for most of the next year,&nbsp; 
and a large part of that time is probationary,&nbsp;
(so if I'm not right for the job, I can stop parting with things! haha)&nbsp;&nbsp; 
but until I get a permanent contract, I'll be living minimalist&nbsp;
and without a washing machine (eek)&nbsp;- 
a good exercise, I think;&nbsp; I have far too many things, and certainly too many clothes. 

I've made a good start on getting rid of things this week,&nbsp;
and deciding on the basics to take with me, when I go, 
but I wasn't really prepared for the sudden sadness&nbsp;
that parting with some things would bring 
(books that I haven't read for years - and probably won't again;&nbsp;
 time to let them go to a good home, etc) 

Ah, well;&nbsp; the sun is shining - another glorious day in May; 
and the Bank Holiday starts for Stuart&nbsp;
as soon as he can get away from the hospital this afternoon. 
Good;&nbsp; gardening&nbsp; together, tomorrow, 
watching the mad hordes of swallows swoop past us this evening, 
and Meeting on Sunday. 
Life is very good. 

Love and blessed be 
xxx

Today is just two years since the day my daughter had her aortic aneurysm,&nbsp;
and spent over eight hours in surgery being kept alve by the wonderful team in Edinburgh Royal Infirmary.
I mention this because, although today will always be an anniversary,&nbsp;
and it was a Day to Remember, followed by some Months to Remember,&nbsp;
its interesting to me how we have moved on,&nbsp; and changed since then.
Life is never quite the same again when you have watched your only child beat the odds!

Last year, approaching the first anniversary of that terrible day, we were all anxious.&nbsp;&nbsp;
My mum and I both admitted to a sense of 'waiting for it to happen again'.&nbsp;&nbsp;
But the year since then has been one of regeneration,&nbsp;
because we decided not to get locked into the emotional teror and freeze-up&nbsp;
that are attached to knowing your child's congenital time bomb has actually exploded.

Laura is alive (isn't she just!) and definitely kicking, so I'm not making a big deal of this,&nbsp;
but this is a good moment to say - that first year was too much of a roller coaster to have anything like emotional clarity;&nbsp;&nbsp;
if this ever happens to you or yours, after the first year, its okay to put life back on track.
No, its essential.
And very good.

love and blessed be
xxx

